('', 'Jeanne Lanvin\'s apartment at the Museum of Decorative Arts', 'Paris', '<iframe src="https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d2624.2686216800867!2d2.3113010506832716!3d48.872155507590634!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x47e66fc8ca981bc9%3A0xe9d6b8346fc38b8f!2s122+Rue+du+Faubourg+Saint-Honor%C3%A9%2C+75008+Paris!5e0!3m2!1sfr!2sfr!4v1501588492226" width="600" height="450" frameborder="0" style="border:0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 200, 2, 'Visites', '122, rue du Faubourg Saint-HonorÃ© ... The mythical address of Maison Lanvin, a symbol of femininity and elegance, is today a prestigious brand recognized throughout the world. Jeanne Lanvin, visionary creator, is also an exceptional woman! Born in 1867, from a poor family, she decided from her childhood to turn her destiny towards the middle of fashion. Modiste at 16, she is passionate about hats. She quickly opened her own workshop and in 1925, she already employed more than 800 seamstresses. In 1897, it was the birth of his only daughter: Marguerite. She becomes her muse, her passion. To celebrate Marguerite\'s thirty years, Jeanne imagines the perfume ArpÃ¨ge: "A musical perfume that murmurs a happy song" (Louise de Villmorin).\r\n<br>\r\nThis visit proposes to you to discover a less known facet of the designer: her taste for the interior decoration. Jeanne bought the old mansion of the Marquise Arconati-Visconti, 16, rue Barbet-de-Jouy in 1920. She had a reception wing built, the halls (hall, library, gallery, dining room) Decorator Armand-Albert Rateau from 1921 to 1924. In the 1920s, Rateau developed a very particular style based on his interest in ancient art and the use of an original bestiary. The three rooms (bathroom, bedroom and boudoir) of the private apartment of Jeanne Lanvin, the great seamstress, decorated in 1924-1925, illustrate a very personal luxury with its bronze furniture with antique patina, oak Or gilded wood. We will discover the taste of the designer for the decoration, as well as her personal life and her finest achievements Haute-couture ....\r\n<br>\r\nThis visit will continue with the discovery of the art deco collections at the Museum of Decorative Arts. The furniture gathered in these rooms illustrates the transition from Art Nouveau to Art Deco around 1910, at a time when the last actors of the previous style, the "builders" like Leon Jallot, EugÃ¨ne Gaillard and the A new decorative art. Among these innovators who announce Art Deco are two trends: decorators, supporters of the return to tradition, such as Paul Iribe and Paul Follot, and the supporters of color such as ClÃ©ment Rousseau, ClÃ©ment MÃ¨re, AndrÃ© Mare and Louis SÃ¼e Announce the richness of Art Deco materials with the use of shagreen, tinted leather, lacquer and painted wood.', 'Tous les jours', 'Jeanne Lanvin\'s apartment at the Museum of Decorative Arts'),
